What I found more concerning, though, was Zuckerberg=E2=80=99s explanation =
of his motivation:

The primary way that I think about this is that we=E2=80=99ve been able to =
show that we can =E2=80=94 we=E2=80=99ve been quite successful at building =
large-scale social experiences within the constraints of platforms that oft=
en our competitors are defining. I think we=E2=80=99re going to be able to =
do even better work. And there=E2=80=99s a lot of things that I would like =
to see us build that we just can=E2=80=99t because of the ways that we=E2=
=80=99re constrained by the competitors who build these platforms. And over=
 time, the main way that I think about this is from a product and mission p=
erspective is we=E2=80=99re here to build awesome experiences that help peo=
ple connect. I think helping to shape the next platform is going to unlock =
that in a profound way for decades to come. And that=E2=80=99s what I=E2=80=
=99m here to do and I think what a lot of people are here to do. So that=E2=
=80=99s kind of the first principles part of this.

From a business perspective, I think that there=E2=80=99s going to end up b=
eing a large business component of this that is Reality Labs-specific. Dire=
ctly, the products that we=E2=80=99re building there and having that be a g=
ood business. But I also think that a lot of this is going to be that it un=
locks a lot of value for the other experiences, the current apps that we ha=
ve, what you think of as the Family of Apps, where we currently, just a lot=
 of the potential value, whether it=E2=80=99s just engagement that could be=
 created, features that we would love to build that we=E2=80=99re not allow=
ed to because Apple or others just don=E2=80=99t allow us to build those th=
ings. And I think that that=E2=80=99s really unfortunate for the industry. =
I think that there=E2=80=99s a lot of lost engagement that would have happe=
ned, a lot of the monetization and value that gets created.

I mean, just look at what happened with App Tracking Transparency, the mass=
ive value destruction for small businesses because of the rules that were s=
et by another platform. And that=E2=80=99s not =E2=80=94 in a future versio=
n of the world, it=E2=80=99s not =E2=80=94 that would be recognized not by =
device sales or some new, like, experience that we=E2=80=99re building in R=
eality Labs. You would basically see that accrue through more efficient mon=
etization of the apps and experiences that we=E2=80=99re building in other =
places. So I think it=E2=80=99s going to be both. But I think this is just =
a very fundamental thing. This is a very long-term bet.

This gets directly at the concern I have about Reality Labs: I can=E2=80=99=
t escape the sense that the entire endeavor feels very solipsistic, motivat=
ed by Zuckerberg=E2=80=99s longstanding desire to be a platform, a motivati=
on that has only taken on more resonance with ATT. The problem, though, is =
that success is a function of consumer preference and adoption, not Meta=E2=
=80=99s need to be free of Apple, but it is the latter that is =E2=80=94 in=
 Zuckerberg=E2=80=99s own words =E2=80=94 Meta=E2=80=99s first principle mo=
tivation.

That said, this point is compelling:

At a deep level, I understand the discomfort that a lot of investors have w=
ith it because it=E2=80=99s just outside of the model of, I think, even mos=
t long-term investors, how you would think about this. And look, I mean, I =
can=E2=80=99t guarantee you that I=E2=80=99m going to be right about this b=
et. I do think that this is the direction that the world is going in. There=
 are 1 billion or 2 billion people who have glasses today. I think in the f=
uture, they=E2=80=99re all going to be smart glasses. And all the time that=
 we spend on TVs and computers, I think that=E2=80=99s going to get more im=
mersive and look something more like VR in the future. And I think that wha=
t we=E2=80=99re seeing is richer ways for people to communicate across even=
 the mobile apps that we have going from text to photos to videos, just a c=
ontinual trend towards being more immersive. So like all of these trends li=
ne up to make me think that this is the right thing. I think we=E2=80=99re =
going to be happy that we did this. So that=E2=80=99s kind of how I think a=
bout it, both from kind of a mission and product perspective, a business pe=
rspective, an investment time frame perspective. But I also understand the =
discomfort that some folks have with something that I can=E2=80=99t put exa=
ct numbers on a near-term time horizon around.

I think that there is a good chance that Zuckerberg is right about the long=
-term trends. The challenge, though, is that good investments aren=E2=80=99=
t just about having the right thesis; they=E2=80=99re about having the righ=
t timing, and Meta is $40+ billion in with scant payoff to show. Even if Re=
ality Labs works out that is a lot of money to make back!

Ultimately, though, Zuckerberg can do what he wants; that is the reality of=
 a founder-led company. And, by the same token, the reality of a founder-le=
d company is that it adapts remarkably quickly to things like AI, or seizes=
 opportunity like it has with Threads, or actually meaningfully re-establis=
hes efficiency as a corporate value. When all of the upsides are weighed in=
 the balance Meta probably still comes out ahead.

